    <exercise id="fs-id3161402" type="problems-exercises"><problem id="fs-id2595255">    <para id="import-auto-id3081407">Calculate the maximum force in newtons exerted by the blood on an aneurysm, or ballooning, in a major artery, given the maximum blood pressure for this person is 150 mm Hg and the effective area of the aneurysm is <m:math><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mtext>20</m:mtext><m:mtext>.</m:mtext><m:mn>0</m:mn><m:mspace width="0.25em"/><m:msup><m:mtext>cm</m:mtext><m:mrow><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:mrow></m:msup></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:math>. Note that this force is great enough to cause further enlargement and subsequently greater force on the ever-thinner vessel wall. </para></problem></exercise>
        <exercise id="fs-id1973660" type="problems-exercises"><problem id="fs-id2932268">    <para id="import-auto-id2655856">During heavy lifting, a disk between spinal vertebrae is subjected to a 5000-N compressional force. (a) What pressure is created, assuming that the disk has a uniform circular cross section 2.00 cm in radius? (b) What deformation is produced if the disk is 0.800 cm thick and has a Young’s modulus of <m:math><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mn>1</m:mn><m:mtext>.</m:mtext><m:mrow><m:mn>5</m:mn><m:mo stretchy="false">×</m:mo><m:msup><m:mtext>10</m:mtext><m:mrow><m:mn>9</m:mn></m:mrow></m:msup></m:mrow><m:mspace width="0.25em"/><m:msup><m:mtext>N/m</m:mtext><m:mrow><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:mrow></m:msup></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:math>?</para></problem>
